    {
      id:"r4-C2-16",
      title:"The Unreliable Witness Within",
      text:"We tend to trust memory as a faithful archive, a recording from which the past may be replayed at will, yet the science of recollection has steadily dismantled this comforting illusion. Memory is not a retrieval but a reconstruction, an act of imaginative assembly performed afresh each time we remember, and in that assembly the present quietly contaminates the past. Every act of recollection subtly revises the memory recalled, so that the events we have remembered most often are frequently the least reliable, polished and distorted by repeated handling like a stone worn smooth in a riverbed. Our recollections are infiltrated by suggestion, reshaped to cohere with the stories we tell about ourselves, and embellished to fill the gaps that the original experience left vacant, all without the faintest sensation of fabrication, for the confabulated and the genuine arrive in consciousness wearing identical garments of conviction. This unsettling truth carries weighty consequences, not least in the courtroom, where the confident testimony of an eyewitness has condemned the innocent on the strength of a certainty that bore no relation to accuracy. Yet there is a strange consolation in this fallibility, for the same plasticity that corrupts the record also frees us from its tyranny, permitting the reinterpretation of past wounds and the gradual reauthoring of the self. We are not the faithful scribes of our own histories but their perpetual editors, and the past we carry is less a fixed document than a living and revisable text, rewritten by the very act of being read.",
      questions:[
        { q:"The author's central claim about memory is that it is:", options:["A faithful and unchanging recording","A reconstruction altered each time we remember","Entirely fictional and never accurate"], answer:1 },
        { q:"Why might frequently recalled memories be 'the least reliable'?", options:["They are too vivid to be wrong","Repeated recollection progressively distorts them","They are rarely important"], answer:1 },
        { q:"That confabulated and genuine memories wear 'identical garments of conviction' means:", options:["We cannot feel the difference between false and true memories","False memories always feel uncertain","True memories are always doubted"], answer:0 },
        { q:"The 'strange consolation' the author finds in memory's fallibility is that:", options:["It makes memory legally reliable","Its plasticity allows us to reinterpret and reauthor our past","It proves memory is perfect"], answer:1 }
      ]
    },
    {
      id:"r4-C2-17",
      title:"The Commons of the Mind",
      text:"There exists a peculiar species of property that defies the ordinary logic of scarcity, for it multiplies rather than diminishes when shared. A loaf of bread divided among ten leaves each with less; an idea explained to ten leaves the teacher no poorer and the world ten minds richer. This is the strange economy of knowledge, the great intellectual commons upon which every civilisation has drawn and to which every generation contributes, a reservoir filled by the dead for the benefit of the unborn. No thinker, however original, fashions his insights from nothing; each erects his modest addition upon a vast inherited scaffolding of language, concept, and prior discovery that he did not create and could not have created alone. Newton's famous remark about standing on the shoulders of giants was less modesty than accurate accounting. Yet this commons is perpetually menaced by the impulse to enclose it, to fence off regions of the shared intellectual landscape and convert what was open to all into the private estate of the few. There is a genuine tension here, for the prospect of reward spurs the labour of invention, and a commons that returns nothing to those who enrich it may starve for want of cultivation. The wise society must therefore navigate between two perils: an enclosure so complete that knowledge ossifies behind paywalls and patents, and a neglect so total that none are moved to add to the common store. To steward the commons of the mind is to balance the incentive to create against the imperative to share, never forgetting that the deepest source of our collective wealth is precisely that which no one can wholly own.",
      questions:[
        { q:"What makes knowledge a 'peculiar species of property'?", options:["It is more expensive than physical goods","It multiplies rather than diminishes when shared","It cannot be communicated"], answer:1 },
        { q:"Newton's remark is cited as 'accurate accounting' to support the point that:", options:["Original thinkers owe a debt to inherited knowledge","Modesty is the highest virtue","No one truly invents anything new"], answer:0 },
        { q:"The 'genuine tension' the author identifies is between:", options:["Sharing freely and rewarding inventors","Old ideas and new ideas","Science and art"], answer:0 },
        { q:"The author's recommended approach is to:", options:["Enclose all knowledge as private property","Eliminate all rewards for invention","Balance incentives to create with the imperative to share"], answer:2 }
      ]
    },
    {
      id:"r4-C2-18",
      title:"The Sculptor of Probability",
      text:"The future does not exist as a fixed destination toward which the present inexorably travels, but rather as a vast fan of possibilities, some near certain, most merely plausible, and many vanishingly improbable, that our actions in the present continually reshape. To think well about what is to come is therefore not to predict, in the manner of an oracle pronouncing fixed decrees, but to sculpt, to lean upon the probabilities, nudging the likely toward the desirable and the disastrous toward the unlikely. This demands a temperament rare among human beings, who are constitutionally drawn toward false certainty, craving the comfort of a single foretold outcome over the vertigo of an open and branching horizon. The competent forecaster cultivates instead a disciplined comfort with ambiguity, holding multiple incompatible futures in mind simultaneously and assigning to each a provisional weight that the arrival of new evidence may revise. He resists the seductive narrative that flattens the manifold contingencies of events into a tidy tale of inevitability, recognising such stories as flattering fictions imposed in hindsight upon what was, at the time, a genuinely uncertain unfolding. There is humility in this stance, but also a quiet form of power, for the one who grasps that the future is plural rather than singular ceases to be its passive subject and becomes, however modestly, its co-author. To sculpt probability is to act within uncertainty without demanding its abolition, to wager thoughtfully where one cannot know for certain, and to accept that the price of meaningful agency is the permanent renunciation of the consoling fantasy that tomorrow is already written.",
      questions:[
        { q:"The author conceives of the future as:", options:["A fixed destination we inevitably reach","A branching fan of possibilities shaped by present action","Entirely unknowable and beyond influence"], answer:1 },
        { q:"The distinction between predicting and sculpting emphasises that good forecasting:", options:["Pronounces fixed outcomes like an oracle","Influences probabilities toward desirable ends","Ignores the future entirely"], answer:1 },
        { q:"Why does the author criticise narratives of 'inevitability'?", options:["They are flattering fictions imposed in hindsight","They are too complex to understand","They predict the future accurately"], answer:0 },
        { q:"The 'price of meaningful agency,' according to the author, is:", options:["Achieving perfect certainty about tomorrow","Giving up the comforting belief that the future is fixed","Refusing to act under any uncertainty"], answer:1 }
      ]
    },
    {
      id:"r4-C2-19",
      title:"The Civilising Restraint",
      text:"Power, it is often observed, reveals character, but a subtler truth is that the deliberate refusal of power reveals it more fully still. Any tyrant can do what he is able; the rarer and more telling virtue lies in declining to do what one could do with impunity. Civilisation, properly understood, is less a matter of capability than of restraint, an intricate web of self-limitations that the strong impose upon themselves in deference to principles that transcend their immediate advantage. The rule of law is precisely this: the astonishing arrangement whereby those who hold the instruments of coercion agree to bind their own hands, submitting their will to procedures that may frustrate their designs. When a powerful party honours a contract it could profitably break, or a victor extends mercy it is under no compulsion to grant, we glimpse the operation of a discipline that distinguishes the civilised from the merely strong. This restraint is perpetually fragile, for it runs against the grain of immediate self-interest and requires each generation to relearn its value, often through the bitter tuition of its absence. The cynic mistakes such forbearance for weakness, failing to perceive that it is in fact the supreme exertion of a strength turned upon itself, the hardest of all victories, which is the victory over one's own capacity for excess. A society endures not by the power it can wield but by the power it consents not to wield, and the measure of its civilisation is found less in what it permits than in what, possessing every means to do, it nonetheless forbids itself.",
      questions:[
        { q:"The author's central paradox is that character is most fully revealed by:", options:["The exercise of unlimited power","The deliberate refusal to use available power","The accumulation of wealth"], answer:1 },
        { q:"The rule of law is described as 'astonishing' because it involves:", options:["The powerful voluntarily binding their own hands","The weak controlling the strong by force","The elimination of all coercion"], answer:0 },
        { q:"The cynic 'mistakes such forbearance for weakness' because the cynic fails to see that restraint is:", options:["A genuine sign of incapacity","The supreme exertion of strength upon itself","Identical to cowardice"], answer:1 },
        { q:"The closing measure of a society's civilisation is found in:", options:["What it permits its citizens to do","What, having every means, it forbids itself","How much power it accumulates"], answer:1 }
      ]
    },
    {
      id:"r4-C2-20",
      title:"The Listener at the Threshold",
      text:"To listen, truly to listen, is among the most demanding and least practised of human disciplines, for it requires the temporary suspension of the self, that ceaseless inner commentator forever rehearsing its reply while the other still speaks. Most of what passes for listening is in fact a species of waiting, an impatient marking of time until the gap into which one may insert one's own preformed thought. Genuine listening, by contrast, entails a willingness to be changed by what one hears, to hold one's own convictions loosely enough that the speaker's words might actually rearrange them. This is no passive reception but an active and arduous generosity, an offering of attention so complete that the listener momentarily stands at the threshold of another's interior world, attempting to inhabit a perspective not his own. Such listening is rare because it is costly; it exposes us to the unsettling possibility that we are mistaken, that the certainties we have built may not survive an honest encounter with a contrary mind. It is far safer to remain sealed within the fortress of our own opinions, granting the other only the courtesy of a hearing while conceding nothing. Yet it is precisely this safety that impoverishes us, for a mind that cannot be moved is a mind that cannot grow, and a conversation in which no participant risks being persuaded is not a dialogue but a duel of monologues. The art of listening, then, is finally an act of courage, a wager that the encounter with another consciousness is worth the surrender of one's own infallibility.",
      questions:[
        { q:"Why does the author say most apparent listening is 'a species of waiting'?", options:["People genuinely absorb everything said","People mark time until they can insert their own reply","People listen too carefully"], answer:1 },
        { q:"Genuine listening is defined chiefly by a willingness to:", options:["Defend one's existing convictions","Be changed by what one hears","Respond as quickly as possible"], answer:1 },
        { q:"The 'fortress of our own opinions' metaphor describes the safety of:", options:["Remaining unmoved and conceding nothing","Listening with full openness","Abandoning all beliefs"], answer:0 },
        { q:"The author ultimately frames listening as an act of:", options:["Passive politeness","Courage that risks one's own infallibility","Intellectual surrender without value"], answer:1 }
      ]
    }
